  "prompt": "How do you stop a sunburn from peeling?",
  "response": "Stopping a sunburn from peeling entirely can be challenging, as peeling is a natural part of the healing process. However, you can take steps to minimize peeling and promote healing:\n\n1. **Moisturize**: Apply a gentle, hydrating moisturizer regularly. Look for products that contain aloe vera or hyaluronic acid, as they can help soothe the skin.\n\n2. **Stay Hydrated**: Drink plenty of water to help keep your skin hydrated from the inside out.\n\n3. **Avoid Picking**: Resist the urge to pick at peeling skin, as this can cause further irritation and increase the risk of infection.\n\n4. **Use Gentle Cleansers**: When washing the affected area, use a mild, fragrance-free cleanser to avoid further irritation.\n\n5. **Cool Compresses**: Apply cool, damp cloths to the sunburned area to relieve discomfort and reduce inflammation.\n\n6. **Limit Sun Exposure**: Stay out of the sun while your skin heals, and wear protective clothing or use a broad-spectrum sunscreen with a high SPF if you must go outside.\n\n7. **Consider Over-the-Counter Remedies**: Products containing hydrocortisone or anti-inflammatory ingredients may help reduce redness and swelling.\n\n8. **Avoid Harsh Products**: Stay away from exfoliants, retinoids, or any harsh skincare products until your skin has fully healed.\n\nIf your sunburn is severe or if you experience blisters, pain, or signs of infection, it's a good idea to consult a healthcare professional for further advice and treatment.",
